98.name: Saw Scaled Viper (Echis carinatus)
98.description: You have been bitten by a Saw Scaled Viper. This species is responsible for more snakebite deaths than all other snake species combined. Saw-scaled vipers are found in the Indian mainland, Pakistan, and Southeast Asia.

95.name: Russells viper (Daboia russelii)
95.description: You have been bitten by a Russells viper. This snake is widely distributed through the Indian mainland and is arguably the major cause of morbidity and mortality related to snakebite envenoming in India.

93.name: Common Indian Cobra (Naja Naja)
93.description: You have been bitten by a common Indian Cobra. Cobras usually hood when threatened or agitated. The most commonly distributed species have the characteristic spectacle marking on the hood.

87.name: King Cobra (Ophiophagus hannah)
87.description: You have been bitten by a King Cobra. The King Cobra is the longest snake from among the venomous species. Adults could have a length of up to 4-5 metres.

64.name: Common Krait (Bungarus caeruleus)
64.description: You have been bitten by a common Krait. There are many species of kraits distributed across the country. Kraits show characteristic thin striated white twin markings across its length.

62.name: Hump Nosed Pit Viper (Hypnale hypnale)
62.description: You have been bitten by a Hump Nosed Pit Viper. They are typically distributed in the Western Ghats throughout the states of Kerala and Karnataka.

54.name: Malabar Pit Viper (Craspedocephalus malabaricus)
54.description: You have been bitten by a Malabar Pit Viper. It is a small snake commonly seen in the Western Ghats of Kerala, Goa and Karnataka.

17.name: Sea Snake
17.description: You have been bitten by a Sea Snake. All sea snakes are venomous and are identified from the characteristic paddle like flattened tails which helps the snake navigate and swim.
